Clinical Neurophysiology

Volume 116, Issue 10, October 2005, Pages 2392-2402

Functional characterization of mismatch negativity to a visual stimulus

Author links open overlay panel, , , , Shigenobu Kanba b,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.clinph.2005.07.006Get rights and content

Abstract

Objective

To record mismatch negativity (MMN) to a visual stimulus fulfilling similar criteria to those of auditory MMN (A-MMN).

Methods

Twelve normal adults were instructed to simultaneously listen to a story and to pay attention to a visual target. Three windmill patterns that differed in the number of vanes (standard, deviant, or target) were used as visual stimuli, and were randomly presented. To ensure endogeneity, standard and deviant stimuli were alternated. To vary differences between frequent (standard) and infrequent (deviant) stimuli, deviants were changed by modulating the number of vanes. To examine effects of physical features of the target stimulus on changes in detection, two target conditions were used. The deviant-related component (DRC) was obtained by subtracting event-related potentials (ERPs) to the deviant stimulus from those to the standard stimulus.

Results

Seven subjects completed all phases of the experiment. Behavioral performances indicated that subjects' attention was directed by auditory context and identification of the target stimulus. Visual DRC appeared 150â€“300 ms after stimulus onset, and consisted of an early (DRN1) and a late (DRN2) component. Magnitude of deviancy from standard stimulus significantly influenced latency of DRN2 but not its magnitude, while changes in target stimulus affected latencies of both DRN1 and DRN2.

Conclusions

Our DRCs satisfied criteria for A-MMN. In contrast to A-MMN, only latency of the DRC was associated with visual sensory discrimination and attentional reorienting.

Significance

It is possible to record valid MMN to a visual stimulus, which allows the study of preattentive visual information processing.

1. Introduction

Processing of preattentive changes in detection has previously been studied by recording auditory mismatch negativity (A-MMN; NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1990, NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen R, 1992). A-MMN is associated with an automatic process which occurs even when the subject's attention is focused away from the evoking stimulus (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1990). It involves an event-related potential (ERP) component that is distributed in the fronto-central area, and is recorded when a sound violates some pre-attentively-detected regularities of the auditory stimulus sequence (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1990, NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen and Alho, 1997, Winkler et al., 2001). Although A-MMN may be elicited under attentional conditions, deviant stimuli may also evoke another negative component (N2b) that overlaps the A-MMN (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1988, NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen et al., 2002). Onset of A-MMN normally begins during the downward slope of N1 deflection and before the N2bâ€“P300 complex which occurs when attention is directed to the stimulus (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1990).

In recent visual ERP studies, negative components in the N2 latency range (150â€“350 ms) have been evoked by using an infrequent deviant stimulus (Czigler et al., 2002, Czigler et al., 2004, Fu et al., 2003, Heslenfeld, 2003, Pazo-Alvarez et al., 2004, Stagg et al., 2004, Tales et al., 1999, Tales et al., 2002). We would like to determine whether these MMN-like waves show exact same functional characterizations that are elicited by deviant stimuli in a visual environment under unattended conditions (Pazoâ€“Alvarez et al., 2003).

Different types of visual stimuli have been used in previous studies, e.g., gratings, photographs, and color screens (Alho et al., 1992, Berti and SchrÃ¶ger, 2004, Cammann, 1990, Czigler et al., 2002, Horimoto et al., 2002, Heslenfeld, 2003, Kenemans et al., 2003, Stagg et al., 2004, Tales et al., 1999, Wei et al., 2002). However, a report suggested that a mismatch response couldn't be obtained by deviant visual stimuli in a visual sequence using gratings (Nyman et al., 1990), and it was concluded that MMN was probably specific to auditory modality.

Although several investigators (Czigler et al., 2002, Czigler et al., 2004, Fu et al., 2003, Heslenfeld, 2003, Pazo-Alvarez et al., 2004, Stagg et al., 2004, Tales et al., 1999, Tales et al., 2002) have partly demonstrated that automatic, endogenous, non-refractory visual counterparts of A-MMN could be recorded for changes in color, spatial frequency and motion, it is still unclear whether all of them share the same properties with A-MMN (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen et al., 2002). If a potential evoked by a visual deviant stimulus occurs under unattended conditions, it should be called a â€˜deviant-related componentâ€™ (DRC; Alho et al., 1992, Wei et al., 2002). Then, if DRC shows properties that fulfill the criteria used for A-MMN including independence of attention, endogeneity, sensory discrimination, and sensory memory (Pazoâ€“Alvarez et al., 2003), it should be considered a valid Vâ€“MMN. Note that little is known about effects of magnitude of deviance on DRC, so we aimed to clarify this issue by fine-grade manipulating magnitude of deviance.

This study consisted of two main aims. First, we determined whether a DRC could be obtained for changes in windmill patterns. Second, if a DRC was present under unattended conditions, we determined functional characteristics of the DRC which were also partly demonstrated by recent studies (Czigler et al., 2002, Czigler et al., 2004, Fu et al., 2003, Heslenfeld, 2003, Pazo-Alvarez et al., 2004, Stagg et al., 2004, Tales et al., 1999, Tales et al., 2002). We anticipated that such procedures warranted the presence of a valid V-MMN that was comparable to A-MMN.

2. Methods

2.1. Subjects

Twelve, right-handed, young healthy adults (4 men, 8 women, 19â€“29 years old) participated in this experiment. All subjects had normal hearing, normal or corrected to normal visual acuity, and no visual diseases. They did not have any history of neurological and mental diseases. Informed consent was obtained after nature and procedures of the experiments were fully explained. Experimental procedures were approved by the Ethics Committee of the Graduate School of Medical Sciences, Kyushu University.

2.2. Stimuli and procedures

Circular blackâ€“white windmill patterns with 90% contrast were generated on a 17-inch CRT monitor, and were controlled using a VSG 2/5 graphics board (Cambridge Research Systems, UK). Diameter of the visual stimulus subtended 5.8Â° at a viewing distance of 114 cm (Fig. 1). Subjects were seated comfortably in a dark room, and were instructed to focus their attention on a story delivered binaurally through earphones, while looking at the center of the monitor. They were also instructed to press a button with their right thumb as soon as they recognized a target stimulus on the screen. Between stimulus runs, they were asked to fill out a questionnaire about the context of the story that they had heard.

Standard (S), deviant (D), and target (T) stimuli were presented in a random order for 200 ms on the computer monitor (Fig. 1). Inter-stimulus interval (ISI) was 800 ms. Stimulus probabilities were 80% (S), 10% (D) and 10% (T).

For comparison with A-MMN, V-MMN should be an endogenous component, and thus for our first set of experiments, it was necessary to exclude any possible exogenous activities derived from changes in stimulus for any DRC obtained in the visual modality. To resolve this issue, S and D stimuli were exchanged. In addition, two different T stimuli were applied to examine effects of physical features of the T stimulus on detection of changes. Three different stimulus conditions were used: (a) a windmill pattern with 6 vanes as S, 24 vanes as D, and 60 vanes as T stimuli (the [S6D24T60] condition), (b) a windmill pattern with 24 vanes as S, 6 vanes as D, and 60 vanes as T stimuli (the [S24D6T60] condition), and (c) a windmill pattern with 6 vanes as S, 24 vanes as D, and a non-patterned white circle as T (the [S6D24T0] condition). Each condition was used in three sessions, and 300 stimuli were presented in each session.

In the second part of our experimental design, we investigated effects of magnitude of deviancy. A-MMN provides a record of experience-dependent memory traces in the human brain. The response is proportional to the relationship between a previous and present stimulus, and should grow larger as the difference between S and D becomes larger (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1992). Thus, S and T stimuli were fixed whereas the number of vanes of D was systematically changed to 12, 18, 24, and 30 vanes (Fig. 1). To investigate effects of magnitude of deviancy, four different conditions were used: (a) a windmill pattern with 6 vanes as S, 12 vanes as D, and 60 vanes as T stimuli (the [S6D12T60] condition), (b) a windmill pattern with 6 vanes as S, 18 vanes as D, and 60 vanes as T stimuli (the [S6D18T60] condition), (c) a windmill pattern with 6 vanes as S, 24 vanes as D, and 60 vanes as T stimuli (the [S6D24T60] condition), (d) a windmill pattern with 6 vanes as S, 30 vanes as D and 60 vanes as T stimuli (the [S6D30T60] condition).

In our third set of experiments, we examined effects of physical features of the T stimulus on DRC. When a windmill pattern is used as a T stimulus, one can argue that discriminative processing between D and T stimuli might affect DRC. To examine this issue, the T stimulus was changed to a non-patterned white circle (T0), which was of an irrelevant pattern to the D stimulus, while the S stimulus was fixed at 6 vanes (S6), and the D stimulus was altered to 12, 18, 24, and 30 vanes (D12, D18, D24, D30; Fig. 1).

2.3. ERP recordings

ERPs were recorded from 18 scalp electrodes placed according to the International 10â€“20 system (Fz, F3, F4, F7, F8, Cz, C3, C4, T3, T4, Pz, P3, P4, T5, T6, Oz, O1, O2). Additional recording electrodes were placed over the left and right mastoid processes. A reference electrode was placed on the tip of the nose. Vertical and horizontal electro-oculograms (EOGs) were also recorded to monitor eye positions. Electrode impedance was maintained below 5 KÎ©. ERPs and EOGs were sampled at 833 Hz with a filter setting of 0.05â€“200 Hz, and data were stored on a disc for off-line analysis. Because S stimuli were presented eight times more often than D and T stimuli, the average number of S responses was equal to that of D stimuli. Recording epoch was 614 ms, including a 72-ms pre-stimulus baseline. To remove high frequency noise, data were bandpass filtered off-line (0.05â€“50 Hz).

2.4. Data and statistical analyses

2.4.1. Behavioral performance

In order to characterize degree of attention, accuracy of answers to questions on the story was evaluated. Questionnaires consisted of 40 questions, for example â€˜What is the name of the hero?â€™ or â€˜How many persons participated in the operation?â€™ In addition, reaction time (RT) and accuracy for T stimuli were also determined to identify any differences in difficulty for each condition. These data were assessed by two-way repeated measures analysis of variance (ANOVA) with two factors, i.e., D (four levels: D12, D18, D24, D30) and T (two level: T0 and T60).

2.4.2. ERP data

Epochs that were contaminated by EOG artifacts, bursts of electromyographic activity, excessive Î± trains, and a peak-to-peak deflection exceeding 100 Î¼V, were excluded from off-line analysis. Actual number of individual epochs averaged for each stimulus ranged from 20 to 55. DRC was obtained by subtracting ERPs elicited by S stimuli from those elicited by D stimuli.

To identify a DRC, mean amplitudes of ERPs evoked by S6 and D during 150â€“300 ms after stimulus onset were compared by a paired tâ€“test. To assess effects of conditions, mean amplitude and peak latencies of DRC were measured. They were evaluated by a three-way repeated measures ANOVA with D (four levels: D12, D18, D24, D30), T (two levels: T0 and T60) and DRC [two levels: early component (DRN1) and late component (DRN2)] as within-subjects factors.

3. Results

Three of the subjects (1 man and 2 women) were excluded from analyses because of excessive artifacts in their ERP recordings. Two subjects (1 man and 1 woman) were not analyzed because of poor performance in the [S6D24T60] or the [S6D30T60] conditions. In the end, only seven subjects completed all phases of the entire experimental protocol.

3.1. Performance data

Mean correctness rate for questions related to the story was 96.7%, thus indicating that subjects were paying attention to the story.

A summary of mean RTs and accuracies for detecting the target (%), for each condition is shown in Table 1. A two-way repeated measures ANOVA for RTs showed a significant main effect of T (F[1,6]=13.69, P=0.01). Interactions between D and T were also significant (F[3,18]=11.26, P=0.0002). Two-way repeated measures ANOVA for accuracy showed that neither the main effect nor interaction was significant. This suggested that detecting T0 stimuli, was much easier than detecting T60 stimuli. Moreover, in the T60 condition, unlike in the T0 condition, when number of vanes of the D stimulus became large (close to that of the T stimulus), RTs tended to be prolonged.

3.2. ERPs

3.2.1. Effects of visual stimuli

Grand averages of ERPs in response to S (red line), D (blue line) and T stimuli (black line) under the [S6D24T60] condition are shown in Fig. 2. A positive (P1)-negative (N1)-positive (P2) deflection was equally elicited by S, D, and T stimuli and was maximum at Oz. This indicated that P1, N1, and P2 components were common exogenous components. The N2 component was elicited by D and T stimuli with a maximum at Cz, but not by S stimuli. The N2bâ€“P3 complex only appeared with the T stimulus, and was maximal at Pz. A summary of peak amplitudes and latencies of P1, N1, P2, N2, and P3 under the [S6D24T60], [S24D6T60] and [S6D24T0] conditions is shown in Table 2.

There was a slight but consistent negative displacement of ERPs in response to D stimuli compared with those with S stimuli, and it was predominant at the occipital and temporal electrodes (Fig. 2). This negative shift usually started during the downward slope of the N1 deflection at a peak latency of approximately 150 ms, and often lasted for approximately 300 ms. This potential was observed in all subjects, and mean amplitudes of ERPs evoked by D stimuli during 150â€“300 ms were significantly more negative than those evoked by S stimuli (P<0.0001, paired tâ€“test). DRC was obtained by subtracting the response to S stimuli from that to D stimuli.

Subtracted waveforms at each electrode under the [S6D24T60] condition are shown in Fig. 3. A DRC was clearly obtained at the occipito-temporal electrodes, and was maximal at Oz. It consisted of two major peaks during 150â€“300 ms: the early DRC (deviant-related negativity 1, DRN1) had a latency of 150â€“200 ms and was present over the parietal area, while the late DRC (deviant-related negativity 2, DRN2) had a latency of 200â€“300 ms and was located over the temporal area.

Grand averages of ERPs (left column) recorded at Oz under different stimulus conditions {[S6D24T60] (top panel), [S24D6T60] (middle panel) and [S6D24T0] (bottom panel)} are shown in Fig. 4. Differences in waveforms (deviant-minus-standard; right column) are also displayed. Changes in the relationships between S, D and T altered latencies and peak amplitudes of N1 in S and D stimuli. However, such manipulations did not abolish DRC.

To confirm these effects, ERP amplitudes elicited by S and D stimuli during three time windows (80â€“140 ms, 140â€“230 ms and 230â€“320 ms) were compared separately. They were evaluated by a two-way ANOVA with the factors of Probability (standard vs. deviant) and Features (6 vs. 24 vanes) as within-subjects factors. In the first time window, i.e., 80â€“140 ms, ANOVA revealed that there was a significant main effect of Features (F[1,6]=60.36, P=0.015) but no main effect of Probability was found. There was also a significant interaction between Probability and Features (F[1,6]=9.69, P=0.048). In the second time window, i.e., 140â€“230 ms, ANOVA revealed that there was a significant main effect of Probability (F[1,6]=57.41, P=0.000), but neither a main effect of Features nor interaction was found. In the third time window, i.e., 230â€“320 ms, there was also a significant main effect of Probability (F[1,6]=45.08, P=0.006), but there were no main effects of Features and Interaction. In other words, the N1 component (80â€“140 ms) was modulated by Features of the stimulus (exogeneity) while DRCs (140â€“230 ms and 230â€“320 ms) were induced by the Probability of the stimulus (endogeneity).

3.2.2. Effects of deviance from standard with alternating target stimuli

Changes in peak latency and mean amplitude of DRC under each condition are shown in Fig. 5. A three-way repeated measures ANOVA for peak latency of DRC showed that there was a significant main effect of D type (F[3,18]=7.03, P<0.01), T type (F[1,6]=7.71, P<0.05) and DRC type (F[1,6]=456.66, P<0.0000). Interactions between D and DRC were also significant (F[3,18]=3.81, P<0.05). Multiple comparisons for the D type were performed. They showed that latency of DRN2 in the D30 condition was significantly shorter than that of D12 (F[1,6]=15.95, P<0.05). A three-way repeated measures ANOVA for mean amplitudes of DRC showed that there was no significant main effect for each factor and interaction. Therefore, alternating D type affected peak latency of DRN2 significantly but not its mean amplitude. Moreover, changing T type affected peak latencies of both DRN1 and DRN2.

4. Discussion

The purpose of this study was to determine whether a component equivalent to the A-MMN existed in conditions of changes in windmill patterns. In the following discussion, we shall determine whether the DRC observed in this study was a valid V-MMN by comparing the findings with properties of A-MMN. We will also highlight new data by comparing the findings in the present study with the current literature.

4.1. Pre-attentive versus attentive processing

A-MMN is an index for early, pre-attentive (automatic) processing of auditory input and is independent of subjects' attention. For a visual modality, a suitable experimental approach would involve maintaining the subject's attention to a continuous task in which the task stimuli are independent of irrelevant ones.

In our experiments, subjects listened to a story throughout the experiments, and the correctness of their answers to a questionnaire related to the story was 96.7%. In addition, accuracy for detecting the correct target was 99%. Such behavioral performance assured us that the subject's attention was divided between auditory context and visual target identification. One may argue that high performance on text memory does not necessary mean that attention was diverted from standard and deviant visual stimuli. Furthermore, this task may use different abilities from those in the visual task. We could not really measure how much the participant's attention shifted to the deviant stimuli. However, irrelevant deviants interfered with target detection due to their close resemblance to the target in the T60 condition in terms of the RT results (Table 1), which in turn implied that deviants did in fact catch the attention of the subject. In contrast, RT results in the T0 condition revealed that irrelevant deviants did not interfere with target identification (Table 1). In addition, the attention-specific N2bâ€“P300 complex (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1990) was elicited only by T stimuli for each condition but not by D stimuli. These results support the idea that subject's attention was almost shifted away from the D stimulus. In accordance with this, there have been several recent studies with careful control of direction of attention (Czigler et al., 2002, Czigler et al., 2004, Heslenfeld, 2003), and DRCs similar to ours were reported. Therefore, even if there was attentional leak toward the D stimulus, we believe that it may not alter our present results significantly.

Because the observed DRC started during the downward slope of the N1 deflection and lasted around 300 ms, and latency of N2b elicited by T stimuli was around 260 ms (Table 2), the DRC could reflect pre-attentive processing as A-MMN does. However, one can argue that this DRC was evoked by attentive processing, e.g., the novel N2, N2b or selection negativity [SN]. Novel stimuli of visual modality have been known to evoke a robust front-centrally N2 component (Kok, 2000, Suwazono et al., 2000), however, our DRC was at a maximum at Oz. Therefore, our DRC was not associated with the novelty of D stimuli. According to NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen (1990), N2b, an attention related component, is evoked by a target stimulus whose amplitude is maximum at Cz. Its scalp distribution is quite different from our DRC. However, SN was observed in a selective attention task of different potentials in which the ERP elicited by a stimulus with an unattended feature value was subtracted from the ERP elicited by the same stimulus when it had an attended feature (Hillyard and Anllo-Vento, 1998, Smid et al., 1999). It is possible that, while targets are detected accurately, there may still be some attention toward the deviants, in which case the DRC may show some properties similar to SN. On the other hand, paradigms associated with MMN are different from those associated with SN; therefore, the two negativities could reflect two independent underlying processes, e.g., one sensitive to relevance and the other one sensitive to probabilities, which operate independently and in parallel (Harter and Aine, 1986). Therefore, even though latency range and distribution on the scalp of SN are similar to those in our DRC, the underling processes may be different by nature.

4.2. Endogeneity versus exogeneity

It has been demonstrated that A-MMN cannot be simply explained by a refractoriness hypothesis, where some neural populations are sensitive to features of a standard stimulus while others respond to features of deviant stimuli (SchrÃ¶ger, 1997). It is, therefore, necessary to rule out all possible exogenous effects of stimulus changes on any DRC obtained in a visual modality. This was controlled in our study by alternating S, D and T stimuli (Fig. 4). Although peak latency and amplitude of N1 were changed, DRC was not abolished by such manipulations. Therefore, DRC seemed to respond to differences between S and D stimuli but not to stimulus features. However, great care should be taken to avoid exogenous effects by frequent stimuli. Because a repetition of the frequent stimulus is essential for evoking MMN, we cannot totally control selective habituation to frequent stimuli (Kenemans et al., 2003). Recently, some investigators have discussed selective habituation in V-MMN studies (Czigler et al., 2002, Czigler et al., 2004, Heslenfeld, 2003, Stagg et al., 2004). We consider it as follows. First, there is evidence that at least parts of the color-related MMN components result from memory comparisons rather than selective habituation (Czigler et al., 2002). Second, the sensory refractory hypothesis predicts an earlier, probably exogenous ERP component (e.g., 80â€“140 ms window), rather than a later, passively endogenous one (140â€“230 ms and 230â€“320 ms windows) (Heslenfeld, 2003). For these reasons, we conclude that the observed DRC probably showed the properties of endogeneity although refractoriness was not fully ruled out.

4.3. Effects of any discriminable changes

Changes in any stimulus feature (tonal frequency, intensity, duration) appear to elicit an A-MMN (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1990) even when changes just approximate the behavioral discrimination threshold. This was proven by combining Aâ€“MMN and psychoâ€“physiological measures in the auditory modality (Amenedo and Escera, 2000). Moreover, amplitude of A-MMN becomes larger when deviants deviate more from standards (SchrÃ¶ger, 1996). This means that amplitude of A-MMN can be an electrophysiological index of change, and it shows the same or greater sensitivity than behavioral measures.

However, the emergence of early negative visual deflection seems to be related to the more salient infrequent stimulus (Czigler and Csibra, 1990, Czigler and Csibra, 1992). Alho et al. (1992) showed that an earlier automatic negative component was only present when D stimuli were maximally different from S stimuli. In a study by Czigler et al. (2002), no obvious V-MMN was elicited by a small deviant condition. Alho et al., 1992, Czigler et al., 2002 interpreted their results as indicating that V-MMN might have a higher threshold than A-MMN.

There are no previous V-MMN studies reporting that the V-MMN component reflects accuracy of the human brain in detecting visual differences, and whether V-MMN parameters correlate with a subject's ability to perceive these differences. In the present study, when D stimuli were systematically changed, mean amplitudes of DRC were not significantly different, however, peak latencies of DRN2 in the D30 condition were significantly shorter than with D12 (Fig. 4). Although we could not really evaluate subject's ability to detect deviant stimuli behaviorally, our findings supported the idea that amplitude of the observed DRC was less sensitive to magnitude of deviation, whereas peak latency of DRN2 was much more sensitive. Further research is necessary to determine whether the observed effects are related to a sensory discrimination process.

4.4. Effects of attention orienting

In the auditory modality, A-MMN is sensitive to subtle changes which do not reflect the orienting response (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 2002). A-MMN consists of two components; one being generated at the auditory cortex in the temporal lobes, and the other is generated in the frontal lobes (Alho, 1995, Giard et al., 1995, NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen, 1995). The temporal component is associated with auditory feature analysis and deviance detection, while the frontal one is associated with involuntary switching of attention to changes in the auditory environment initiated by the auditory-cortex deviance-detection mechanism (Rinne et al., 2000). In our study, differences between the T0 stimulus and S6 stimulus were much clearer than those between the T60 and S6 stimuli. Although there was no significant difference in accuracy for each condition, RT in the T0 condition was significantly shorter than that in the T60 condition. Obviously, the T0 condition was a much easier task (no need to differentiate the windmill patterns), therefore the subject's attention might shift faster in the T0 condition than in T60. Target change did not affect mean amplitude of both DRN1 and DRN2, but affected latencies which were shorter in the T60 condition than in T0. Therefore, peak latency may be associated with attentional switching or orienting responses.

4.5. Scalp topography of DRC

In the auditory modality, polarity reversal of A-MMN has been observed bilaterally at the mastoid processes (NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen et al., 1989, NÃ¤Ã¤tÃ¤nen R, 1992). Source localization techniques have been applied to electrical and magnetic ERPs (Hari, 1991, Sams et al., 1991) and recordings from the surface of the temporal lobe have also been performed (Kropotov et al., 1995). Neural generators of A-MMN are situated in the temporal association cortex anterior to the primary auditory projection area. Although distribution of sources of V-MMN is less precisely known than that of A-MMN, they may be present with maximum amplitudes at the specific-modality cortex, such as the occipital cortex and infero-temporal cortex contralateral to the stimulated visual field (Woods et al., 1992) and occipital pole (Berti and SchrÃ¶ger, 2001, Berti and SchrÃ¶ger, 2004, Czigler et al., 2002, Czigler et al., 2004, Kenemans et al., 2003). Such components have been found at the occipital and posterior temporal areas (Alho et al., 1992, Heslenfeld, 2003, Nordby et al., 1996, Stagg et al., 2004, Tales et al., 1999, Tales et al., 2002), and at the occipito-parietal regions with right hemispheric predominance (Cammann, 1990). In contrast, there have been a few reports which showed a frontal component together with occipital negative ones (Berti and SchrÃ¶ger, 2001, Czigler et al., 2002, Heslenfeld, 2003, Wei et al., 2002). Although only midline electrodes, except for Oz, were used, there was a report on the frontoâ€“central negative component (Iijima et al., 1996). These frontal components may be associated with attention orienting, but not with modality specificity. In the present study, both DRN1 and DRN2 peaked at the occipital area, but DRN2 had a much broader distribution than that of DRN1 (Fig. 3). In addition, DRN1 extended to the parietal area, while DRN2 extended to the temporal area. Therefore, DRC might have two different sources. Interestingly, this finding remarkably resembled that of Heslenfeld (2003). He considered that his two DRCs might be analogous to A-MMN, but he did not discuss physiological differences. In the present experiments, DRN2 was affected by attentional orienting, but DRN1 was not. These findings support the idea that DRN1 purely reflects automatic processing of change detection, while DRN2 results from involuntary attention shift triggered by DRN1. Further studies with higher spatial resolution are required to resolve this issue.

4.6. Is a valid V-MMN present?

Although V-MMN-like responses have been reported to novel, oddball, or unexpected visual stimuli, they have not been regarded as valid V-MMNs (Pazo-Alvarez et al., 2003). The main methodological limitations were a lack of control over (or failure to control) attentional, exogenous, and refractory effects of V-MMN. (Alho et al., 1992, Berti and SchrÃ¶ger, 2001, Cammann, 1990, Csibra and Czigler, 1991, Czigler and Csibra, 1990, Czigler and Csibra, 1992, Horimoto et al., 2002, Iijima et al., 1996, Kenemans et al., 1992, Nordby et al., 1996, Nyman et al., 1990, Tales et al., 1999, Tales et al., 2002, Wei et al., 2002, Woods et al., 1992). Recently, Czigler et al., 2002, Czigler et al., 2004 have conducted studies taking these problems into consideration. They used colored vertical square-wave gratings or checkerboards as stimuli and instructed the subjects to respond to the target stimulus which was presented at the center of a 15 inch monitor. Under their experimental conditions, subject's attention was directed to the center of the monitor, and away from the peripheral stimulus field. Thus, they concluded that V-MMN occurred in response to changes in color at the posterior site during 140â€“200 ms range, and was free of refractory effects. Although they did not observe V-MMN in small deviance conditions, they stressed that larger stimulus differences were necessary to elicit V-MMN compared to the A-MMN component as Alho et al. (1992) did.

The DRC in our results resembled A-MMN because it occurred automatically while the focus of attention was directed away from the evoking stimuli. Overall, the DRN during the period around 150â€“300 ms after stimulus onset in the present study satisfied criteria for A-MMN. Therefore, we believe that V-MMN may exist when a researcher carefully controls the visual stimulus with shifting the focus of attention away from the deviant stimulus. However, there is no reason to believe that underlying mismatch detection mechanisms should be identical in both sensory modalities due to the existence of anatomical and functional differences (Pazoâ€“Alvarez et al., 2003). In accordance with this notion, we found that DRN1 and DRN2 had different behaviors than A-MMN. Criteria for A-MMN are: (1) independence of attention, (2) endogeneity, (3) sensory discrimination, (4) sensory memory, and (5) association of attention orienting. DRC showed the properties of independence of attention, endogeneity, visual sensory discrimination, and association of attention orienting but there was no evidence for a memory-based mismatch detection in the present study. Although there are a few reports supporting the idea that DRC is a memory based phenomenon (Czigler et al., 2002, Fu et al., 2003, Pazo-Alvarez et al., 2004), further studies including changes in probabilities of standard stimulus or lengthening of the inter-stimulus intervals are necessary to prove whether DRC to a windmill pattern stimulus has the properties of sensory memory. In any case, we believe that in our study, DRC reflected at least pre-attentive automatic visual information processing.

5. Conclusions

Our results confirmed that valid V-MMNs could be obtained from a windmill pattern stimulus. Latency of DRN2 was significantly modulated by deviancy. Therefore, it is possible to detect and assess correlations of pre-attentive processing in the visual modality by measuring ERPs to a windmill pattern.
